ore than an order of magnitude less to in excess of the economic impacts. Conclusions. Our analyses indicate that the public health impacts of congestion may be significant enough in magnitude, at least in some urban areas, to be considered in future evaluations of the benefits of policies to mitigate congestion. {\^{A}}{\textcopyright} 2010 Levy et al; licensee BioMed Central Ltd.},
